WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.520
This is how to use Positron's layout to make your data science life easier.

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:06.680
When you're working with data, keeping track of your variables, plots, and outputs can

00:00:06.680 --> 00:00:07.680
get messy fast.

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:09.280
Positron was built with that in mind.

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:11.320
Here's how its layout helps you stay organized.

00:00:11.320 --> 00:00:14.080
First when you open up Positron, you'll notice there's three main areas.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:15.080
There's the script pane.

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:16.580
This is where you'll write your code.

00:00:16.580 --> 00:00:20.200
There's the console pane, where you'll access the terminal and see results and errors.

00:00:20.200 --> 00:00:21.440
And then there's the side panes.

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:23.799
This is where things get really useful for your data workflows.

00:00:23.799 --> 00:00:27.200
This will give you a live view of your data frames and variables, their types and shapes,

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:28.400
and quick summary you can click into.

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:32.480
You can literally click on a data frame variable and it will open up a spreadsheet-style viewer.

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:34.040
Then there's a pane for visualizations.

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:37.619
When you run a plot command with matplotlib, seaborn, or plotly, the chart will pop up

00:00:37.619 --> 00:00:39.360
in the plots tab of the output pane.

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:41.720
You can scroll, zoom, and even export it with one click.

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:45.520
Instead of bouncing between your code editor, a browser, a terminal, and a jupyter tab,

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:48.639
Positron gives you a clean layout for writing and running your code, real-time view of your

00:00:48.639 --> 00:00:51.680
variables and charts, and built-in tools for interactivity and visualizations.

00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:54.840
